If you want a lightweight, copy‑and‑paste starting point, here’s a small HTML/CSS scaffold that reflects the sections we’ve outlined.  
It keeps the tone neutral and the disclaimers clear, so anyone can host it responsibly.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Community Recovery Support Worksheet</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      line-height: 1.6;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      color: #222;
      background-color: #f8f9fa;
    }
    header {
      background-color: #3d7f89;
      color: #fff;
      text-align: center;
      padding: 1.5rem;
    }
    section {
      max-width: 800px;
      margin: 2rem auto;
      padding: 1rem;
      background-color: #fff;
      border-radius: 4px;
      box-shadow: 0 0 4px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
    }
    h2 {
      border-bottom: 2px solid #3d7f89;
      padding-bottom: 0.25rem;
    }
    .shaded {
      background-color: #e9f3f5;
      padding: 1rem;
      border-radius: 4px;
    }
    footer {
      text-align: center;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      padding: 1rem;
      color: #555;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Community Recovery Support Worksheet</h1>
    <p>Free self‑help reflection and crisis‑response guide</p>
  </header>

  <section class="shaded">
    <h2>Read This First</h2>
    <p>You are not alone. Cravings and setbacks don’t mean failure—they’re signals that you need care and gentleness. This page is a personal support guide, not a treatment plan. Use it to reflect and stay connected to licensed help and peer support.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Download or Open Worksheet</h2>
    <p><a href="#">Download Fillable PDF</a> | <a href="#">Printable Version (PDF)</a></p>
    <p><em>Free to share; see terms of use.</em></p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>About This Resource</h2>
    <p>The worksheet was created by volunteers and educators as a community wellbeing aid. It collects self‑help techniques into a single, easy‑to‑use page for personal reflection or peer‑support meetings.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Peer‑Support Sharing Note</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Respect each participant’s privacy.</li>
      <li>Offer compassion, not medical advice.</li>
      <li>Use emergency contacts if anyone is in crisis.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
    <p>This resource offers general self‑help information. It is not professional counseling, therapy, or medical advice. If you or anyone around you is in danger or experiencing a crisis, call your local emergency number.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>U.S. – SAMHSA 1‑800‑662‑HELP (4357)</li>
      <li>Canada – Wellness Together Canada wellnesstogether.ca</li>
      <li>U.K. – FRANK 0300 123 6600</li>
      <li>Australia – Lifeline 13 11 14</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <footer>
    <p><em>You deserve support, safety, and time to heal.</em><br />
    Community Recovery Resource – Open, Non‑Commercial Guide<br />
    Self‑Help Aid – Not a Substitute for Professional Treatment</p>
  </footer>
</body>
</html>
```

This skeleton keeps the text accessible, responsive, and easy for a volunteer developer to expand.  
Would you like notes on embedding downloadable versions (PDF, DOCX) or linking to an online form version safely?

