Here’s a quick CSS addition you can drop into your existing `<style>` block to make that change‑log table mobile‑friendly.  
It keeps the transparency of the information but lets the table reflow cleanly on smaller screens.

```css
/* Responsive table for Change Log */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  table, thead, tbody, th, td, tr {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
  }

  thead tr {
    display: none; /* hide header row on small screens */
  }

  tbody tr {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 0.5rem;
    background-color: #fff;
  }

  td {
    border: none;
    padding: 4px 8px;
  }

  td::before {
    content: attr(data-label);
    font-weight: bold;
    display: block;
    color: #3d7f89;
  }
}
```

And update each `<td>` in your table with a `data-label` attribute so screen‑readers and narrow layouts know which heading applies:

```html
<td data-label="Date">2024‑06‑15</td>
<td data-label="Version">1.0</td>
<td data-label="Summary of Updates">
  Initial publication with worksheet, crisis checklist, and disclaimers.
</td>
<td data-label="Reviewed By">J. Doe, Accessibility Lead</td>
```

On full screens the table appears normally; on phones or small tablets each row becomes a tidy card with labeled fields.  

